    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B02",
      "act": "COLD OPEN",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10.0,
      "narration_text": "Two groups studied the same material. The fluent group \u2014 smooth notes, easy reading \u2014 scored 85% on the immediate exam. The frictional group \u2014 confused, practicing retrieval \u2014 scored 70%. One week later, the scores flipped.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "trace"
      },
      "scene_class": "B02_StudyComparison",
      "actual_duration_s": 14.89,
      "audio_file": "../vox-two-clocks/mp3/beat-B02.mp3",
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-two-clocks/clips/B02.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-two-clocks/mp3/beat-B02.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B03",
      "act": "THE QUESTION",
      "estimated_duration_s": 7.0,
      "narration_text": "Why does the method that feels most productive \u2014 smooth, fluent, comfortable \u2014 leave the least behind? And why does struggle often mean learning is actually happening?",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "question",
        "remotion": {
          "pattern": "SlateCard",
          "provenance": "proven-core/SlateCard",
          "version": "1",
          "props": {
            "headline": "Why does the method that feels most productive \u2014 smooth, fluent,\u2026",
            "eyebrow": "THE QUESTION",
            "topic": "COMPUTATIONAL SKEPTICISM"
          },
          "rendered": {
            "out": "media/B03.mp4",
            "at": ""
          }
        }
      },
      "card": {
        "kind": "question",
        "copy": "Why does the method that feels most productive leave the least behind \u2014 and why does struggle mean learning is happening?"
      },
      "actual_duration_s": 9.43,
      "audio_file": "../vox-two-clocks/mp3/beat-B03.mp3",
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-two-clocks/clips/B03.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-two-clocks/mp3/beat-B03.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "act": "THE PROBLEM",
      "estimated_duration_s": 8.0,
      "narration_text": "The natural assumption: higher performance in practice means more learning. So the fluent method, which produces the highest performance, should produce the most learning.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "scene_class": "B04_NaivePicture",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.51,
      "audio_file": "../vox-two-clocks/mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-two-clocks/clips/B04.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-two-clocks/mp3/beat-B04.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "act": "THE PROBLEM",
      "estimated_duration_s": 8.0,
      "narration_text": "But performance and learning run on different clocks. The conditions that produce the best performance in the moment are often the worst conditions for long-term learning.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "trace"
      },
      "scene_class": "B05_TwoClocks",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.62,
      "audio_file": "../vox-two-clocks/mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "locked": true,
      "source_clip": "../vox-two-clocks/clips/B05.mp4",
      "source_audio": "../vox-two-clocks/mp3/beat-B05.mp3"
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "act": "THE MECHANISM",
      "estimated_duration_s": 5.0,
      "narration_text": "The confusion is the teaching signal.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "STILL",
        "source": "ai",
        "motion": "kenburns",
        "remotion": {
          "pattern": "SlateCard",
          "provenance": "proven-core/SlateCard",
